<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9479&amp;p=134070#p134070"><![CDATA[
Thanks!<br /><br />Let's see, MAD2A_VCC5V_NOBAT.LOG shows all ok. But MAD2A_CLK_VCC5V_NOBAT.LOG didn't work as expected...<br /><br />Oops, I've screwed up the CLK test,<br /><span style="color: #40FF00">&quot;test byte ptr ds:[out_val],40h       ; (inverted OSC signal)&quot;</span><br />should have been:<br /><span style="color: #40FF00">&quot;test byte ptr ds:[out_val],80h       ; (inverted OSC signal)&quot;</span><br />Here's the fixed version: Mad2clk.zip that should avoid the &quot;bad&quot; results (for VCC &gt; VBAT cases).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">SkinnyV wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I know that Centronics pin 32 - /ERR is DB25-Pin15 But when you say Centronics pin 9, would it be the same pin on the DB25 connector?<br /></div><br />Yes, pin 9 is pin 9 (MSB of the eight DATA lines) on either Centronics or DB25.<br /><br />And the other voltages, VCC3V_NOBAT is same as VCC5V_NOBAT. Makes sense since both have VCC &gt; VBAT.<br />And VCC3V_VBAT3V and VCC5V_VBAT5V both have the /SRAM signal forced high, also makes sense since they have VCC = VBAT.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5211">nocash</a> — Fri Sep 19, 2014 10:52 pm</p><hr />
