<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: MAD-1, MAD-2, MAD-R differences?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9479&amp;p=133221#p133221"><![CDATA[
Thanks for the MAD-2 tests! The logic looks same as in MAD-1 (except for the RESET pin).<br />Sorry, about the late reply (been busy with nintendo dsi stuff last 1-2 weeks).<br /><br />Here's an updated version of the test package: Mad2.zip with two new test programs (since the parallel port doesn't have enough pins to do all tests at once):<br /><br /><strong>MAD2.COM</strong> this tests the MAD-1-style behaviour on all pins (except for the RESET pin acting different as MAD-1). It's also toggling the additional OSC input (MAD2 Pin9, which needs to be wired to Centronics Pin9, in case you don't already have it connected as so) (the OSC signal does probably not effect the outputs checked by MAD2.COM). Theoretically, the test program should display &quot;ok&quot; for all tests with the current wiring.<br /><br /><strong>MAD2CLK.COM</strong> for this test, please replace the Centronics Pin32 (/ERR) connection: Wire it to MAD-2 Pin10 (/OSC) instead of MAD-2 Pin18 (/ROM0). With that wiring, the test program should display &quot;ok&quot; everywhere, too (assuming the /OSC pin outputs the opposite voltage of OSC).<br /><br />As far as I remember, you've tested 7 combinations for the other MAD chips:<br />  VbatGND_VCC5V<br />  Vbat3V_VCCGND<br />  Vbat3V_VCC3V<br />  Vbat3V_VCC5V<br />  Vbat5V_VCCGND<br />  Vbat5V_VCC3V<br />  Vbat5V_VCC5V<br />If you want to test the different VBAT and VCC supply voltages for MAD-2 too: It might be enough to test the voltages with MAD2CLK.ROM only. The test program doesn't test the /ROM0 pin - but it does test /ROM1 (and one might assume that /ROM0 behaves similar as /ROM1 concerning the supply voltages, so it isn't really necessary to test it with MAD2.COM).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5211">nocash</a> — Thu Aug 28, 2014 6:23 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
