<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9479&amp;p=131486#p131486</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9479&amp;p=131486#p131486"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: MAD-1, MAD-2, MAD-R differences?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9479&amp;p=131486#p131486"><![CDATA[
Hi SkinnyV, sorry for not replying earlier... for the logic table test, best wire it like this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent"> Centronics Side          MAD-1 Chip Side                MAD-2<br /> DATA CNTR.2..9  -------- IN0..7 (Pin17..11,9)         ___  ___<br /> /ERR CNTR.32    -------- OUT0 (Pin18)  /ROM.CS1 OUT1 |1  \/ 18| OUT0 /ROM.CS0<br /> SLCT CNTR.13    -------- OUT1 (Pin1)   /SRAM.CS OUT2 |2     17| IN0  ADDR0<br /> PE   CNTR.12    -------- OUT2 (Pin2)    /AUX.CS OUT3 |3     16| IN1  ADDR1<br /> /ACK CNTR.10    -------- OUT3 (Pin3)    /ROM.CS OUT4 |4     15| IN2  ADDR2<br /> BUSY CNTR.11    -------- OUT4 (Pin4)            Vout |5     14| IN3  ADDR3<br /> N/A  N/A             --- Vout (Pin5)             VCC |6     13| IN4  /CART<br /> VCC  +5VDC      -------- VCC  (Pin6)            Vbat |7     12| IN5  MODE<br /> GND  CNTR.19-30 -------- VBat (Pin7)             GND |8     11| IN6  /RESET<br /> GND  CNTR.19-30 -------- GND  (Pin8)        OSC  IN7 |9_____10| OUT5 /OSC</div><br /><br />The circuit is 1:1 same as for the 16pin chips, except there are two new extra pins at the bottom:<br />MAD2.Pin9 (IN7) wired to Centronics.Pin9.<br />MAD2.Pin10 (OUT5) left not connected for now (in later tests it could be swapped with OUT5 for example, so one could test either of the two pins).<br /><br />For the test software, please give it a try with the old MAD-1 and MAD-R test programs (both of them).<br /><br />They won't toggle the IN7 input yet, and certainly can't check the unconnected OUT5 pin, but the test results will help to figure out if the MAD-2 behaves more like a MAD-1, or more like a MAD-R (or if it behaves like neither one of them).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">nocash wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">current version of the program is already using all 5 inputs on the parallel port<br /></div>Couldn't you use the control pins as inputs?</div><br />No, rather not. The control lines have been bi-directional only on very old printer ports (those with one-directional data lines). But as far as I know, the control lines are output-only on all newer parallel ports (anything produced in past 20 years or so).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5211">nocash</a> — Thu Jul 24, 2014 11:53 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
